text: WeWork locations, on average (?), reach >80% occupancy within 6 months. pic.twitter.com/NNmOTqQ9Ov

name: drorpoleg
text: WeWork Costs: Net "capital expenses per desk added" have decreases 50% from 2014 to 2019. Nice, but probably due to expansion in secondary and developing markets. Need to see what things look like if the company focuses on its strongest markets (NYC etc.) pic.twitter.com/D0D1afbLRe

name: drorpoleg
text: WeWork's Immediate Steps: Divest various acquisitions Reduce headcount of management layer, acquisitions, and growth team NOT to touch the community team Expand focus on enterprise, particularly with existing clients pic.twitter.com/NjvTqcqUHP

name: drorpoleg
text: WeWork Evolution: - From founder-led to "Executive" led - From distracted to focused - From small & mid-sized customers to enterprise customers - From signing leases BEFORE getting funded to more "disciplined" expansion in profitable markets pic.twitter.com/rpOBJuPLBw

name: drorpoleg
text: WeWork Customer Churn: - 580,000 current members - 4% gross churn - 121% retention rate (meaning, on average, customers add more desks over time rather than reduce them) - Churn is declining over time, partly thanks to shift to enterprise customers

name: drorpoleg
text: WeWork Source of Profit: - Buy space, materials, & services in bulk - Scaled construction platform with "standardized build-out sand procedures" - Subsidies from landlords (due to scale) - Utilizing space "more efficiently than any lesson we know of" while optimizing experience

name: drorpoleg
text: WeWork Customer Groups: 43% of memberships are from enterprise customers. But the company emphasizes the fact that smaller customers are "the most poorly served" by current landlords and agents.

name: drorpoleg
text: WeWork Scale: - 600 locations, 122 cities, 32 countries - 676,000 active desks + pipeline of 969k desks. First slide already makes it hard to tell whether "337k non-mature desks" are part of the pipeline or part of the "active" ones. - $4.2 billion revenue run rate

name: uwsgeezer
text: Indeed, New York has quite a few newish spaces, which may explain why WeWork only made $1 million gross profit (not contribution margin) in the city in the first half of 2019. pic.twitter.com/vEMLPrcnf9

name: uwsgeezer
text: I spent time in a young, New York WeWork location and it was disconcertingly empty. https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/24/business/wework-growth.html …pic.twitter.com/5Wc0gr2qDp

name: uwsgeezer
text: And there are so many of them. ***Nearly half*** of WeWork’s 600 locations are under a year old. Investors would have asked whether they had been built too fast and whether enough of them would get to a 20% contribution margin. pic.twitter.com/NTYLwQdjyk

name: uwsgeezer
text: Why didn’t WeWork let the world know about the 21% margin during the IPO? Hard to tell. Maybe investors would only have paid an IWG multiple for IWG profitability? But my hunch was that showing the mature locations would also reveal the performance of the younger spaces.

name: uwsgeezer
text: WeWork says its mature locations -- those at least 2 years old – have a contribution margin of 21 percent. How good is that? pic.twitter.com/AasCa1r9Ih

name: uwsgeezer
text: Why did the numbers -- put together last month -- go out this evening? My guess: WeWork’s management wants to show (restless/angry) employees and outsiders that its core business has a future.

name: uwsgeezer
text: So, WeWork put out a lot of new numbers this evening – disclosures that many expected to see in the IPO filings, but weren’t there. Back then, we noted the numbers’ absence. WeWork has turned an important page in releasing them. Kudos. https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/29/business/wework-ipo.html …

name: WeWorkersCo
text: We want to work with you. Please join us in writing a better ending to this chapter of the WeWork story.

name: WeWorkersCo
text: With this letter we are introducing ourselves, the WeWorkers Coalition. We are taking full advantage of our legal right to establish this coalition, and in doing so, we hope to give the future employees of WeWork the voice we never had.

name: WeWorkersCo
text: In the long term, we want the employees who remain at WeWork, and those who join in the future, to inherit something positive we left behind. We want them to never find themselves in this position again, and for that to happen, they need a voice.

name: WeWorkersCo
text: Those of us who have visas through WeWork need assistance and adequate time to find a new employer to sponsor our respective visas.

name: WeWorkersCo
text: We don’t want to be defined by the scandals, the corruption, and the greed exhibited by the company’s leadership. We want to leave behind a legacy that represents the true character and intentions of WeWork employees.

name: WeWorkersCo
text: This is a company that has inspired many of us, challenged us, and has been a formative personal and professional experience for those of us who began our careers here. WeWork has been not just a workplace, but a source of friendships and inspiration along the way.

name: WeWorkersCo
text: WeWork’s company values encourage us to be “entrepreneurial, inspired, authentic, tenacious, grateful and together.” Today, we are embracing these qualities wholeheartedly as we band together to ensure the well-being of our peers.

name: WeWorkersCo
text: Tuesday we introduced ourselves to management. Today we are introducing ourselves to the world. We are a coalition of WeWork employees seeking immediate action and a long term seat at the table. This is the letter we delivered to We Company management.
